48
04:53.010 --> 05:00.690
through the circuit, evaluating
the gates appropriately, then we see that the final value
on this wire here is a one.

49
05:00.690 --> 05:09.480
So the entire circuit describes
a sequence of operations that are composed as the figure suggests, and we end up with a function
from two bits to one bit

50
05:09.480 --> 05:16.380
in this particular case. But in general, there could be any number
of input and output bits.

51
05:16.380 --> 05:23.250
This particular circuit happens to compute the exclusive OR of the two input bits, so the output is a one
if and only if exactly

52
05:23.250 --> 05:31.680
one of the two input bits is set to a one and the other one is set to a zero, but that's not really
important, it's just an example.

53
05:31.680 --> 05:38.190
It's a basic fact about Boolean circuits that any function from any number of bits to any number of bits can be computed

54
05:38.190 --> 05:46.740
by some Boolean circuit, although sometimes you might
need a very large circuit to compute the function
that you're interested in.

55
05:46.740 --> 05:50.250
There are other styles that
are used to describe circuits.

56
05:50.250 --> 05:56.823
For example, this figure
represents exactly the same circuit as we had before, using a style that's perhaps more typical

57
05:56.823 --> 06:03.990
in electrical engineering, where there are conventions for the shapes that represent different gates.

58
06:03.990 --> 06:11.910
We aren't going to use
this particular style, but we will introduce
some symbols of our own for different quantum gates, such as Hadamard gates,
Controlled NOT gates,

59
06:11.910 --> 06:15.300
Toffoli gates, and so on.

60
06:15.300 --> 06:20.640
Just as an aside, here we can see the origin
of the term circuit.

61
06:20.640 --> 06:27.540
In the context of electrical engineering, it's very natural to
think about electricity cycling through a circuit.

62
06:27.540 --> 06:35.010
But in this series we're not
talking about electricity moving through circuits, we're talking about information
moving through circuits.

63
06:35.010 --> 06:44.760
And once again for us, they will always be acyclic, where the information
moves from left to right.

64
06:44.760 --> 06:49.530
Here's a different example of
a different type of circuit called an arithmetic circuit.

65
06:49.530 --> 06:58.410
This time the wires store numbers and the gates represent
arithmetic operations such as addition and multiplication.

66
06:58.410 --> 07:01.410
Here you can see an example
of an arithmetic circuit.

67
07:01.410 --> 07:10.350
It's not important for the sake
of this lesson what it does, it's just an example that's
meant to convey the idea that there are different
notions of circuits.

68
07:10.350 --> 07:17.490
We can also think about
circuits involving randomness, for instance, where the gates represent
probabilistic operations, and if you felt like it,

69
07:17.490 --> 07:25.680
you could probably sit around all day dreaming up new models of computation based on the notion of circuits.

70
07:25.680 --> 07:35.100
In the quantum circuit model,
the wires represent Qubits, and the gates represent both unitary operations and measurements.

71
07:35.100 --> 07:38.880
Here's a very simple example
of a quantum circuit.

72
07:38.880 --> 07:45.420
There's just one Qubit in this circuit, which is represented
by the horizontal line, and the gates, which are
indicated by squares,

73
07:45.420 --> 07:48.870
represent unitary operations that are performed on this Qubit.

74
07:48.870 --> 07:53.700
So there are no measurements
in this particular example.

75
07:53.700 --> 08:00.750
If we want to give the
Qubit a name such as X, we can indicate that in the diagram by putting an X right
here, that's optional.

76
08:00.750 --> 08:10.680
Just like we had for the Boolean circuit from a few moments ago, we can think about this circuit
as representing a sequence of operations where time
goes from left to right.

77
08:10.680 --> 08:17.610
So we start out with X,
we apply the first gate, which is a Hadamard gate
followed by an S gate,

78
08:17.610 --> 08:20.910
then another Hadamard
gate, and finally a T gate.

79
08:20.910 --> 08:26.910
We saw these operations
toward the end of lesson one, and here you can see
their matrix descriptions.

80
08:26.910 --> 08:35.850
So when we perform these
four operations in order, which means first H, then
S, then H again, and then T,

81
08:35.850 --> 08:42.240
the combined operation is given
by this product right here, keeping in mind that the order
essentially gets reversed

82
08:42.240 --> 08:48.810
as we talked about in lesson one. If we perform the matrix multiplication, we get this matrix right here,

83
08:48.810 --> 08:55.980
and so the action of the
circuit on the Qubit X is described by this unitary matrix.

84
08:55.980 --> 09:04.890
Sometimes we'd like to indicate explicitly in a quantum circuit diagram
what input we're feeding in, and we can do that as you see right here.

85
09:04.890 --> 09:07.890
In this case, we're inputting
Ket 0 into the circuit.

86
09:07.890 --> 09:13.830
That's pretty common. We often take Ket 0 to
be the initialized state of a Qubit, but that's not necessary.

87
09:13.830 --> 09:18.060
We could also consider
applying the circuit to a different state.

88
09:18.060 --> 09:26.100
If we choose to, we can also
indicate the output state that we get like this.

89
09:26.100 --> 09:33.660
Here's another example where
this time we have two Qubits named X and Y as you
can see in the diagram.

90
09:33.660 --> 09:40.770
Here we have a Hadamard gate, which is being applied to the Qubit Y, followed by the gate that's indicated by
this symbol right here,

91
09:40.770 --> 09:47.730
which is a Controlled NOT gate. We talked about the
Controlled NOT operation in the previous lesson,

92
09:47.730 --> 09:54.570
and here in this diagram we
can see that the control Qubit is Y, which is indicated by
the small filled in circle,

93
09:54.570 --> 10:01.560
and the target Qubit is X, which is indicated by the large circle with what looks like a plus sign in it.

94
10:01.560 --> 10:05.580
It kind of looks like the
symbol for the exclusive OR so it makes sense.

